oral relief programs, Kressel proposes an alternative program whereby the region's states would promote a brand of pastoralism that preserves rangeland herding while keeping in step with the contemporary cultural and political context. This truly visionary set of recommendations would have several dividends, especially for the Bedouin: their cultural legacy, in danger of obsolescence, would be preserved while at the same time enhancing both their pastoral skills and ability to secure a livelihood from herding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aApplied anthropologyzIsrael. 0aApplied anthropologyzMiddle East. 0aBedouinsxDomestic animalszMiddle East. 0aBedouinsxLand tenurezMiddle East. 0aDesert conservationzIsrael. 0aDesert conservationzMiddle East. 0aPastoral systemszIsrael. 0aPastoral systemszMiddle East. 0aShepherdszIsrael. 0aShepherdszMiddle East. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791486467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791486467/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles